    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <queue>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n, m; cin >> n >> m;\n  vector<vector<int>> g(n);\n  for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {\n    int u, v; cin >> u >> v;\n    g[u].push_back(v);\n    g[v].push_back(u);\n  }\n\n  // BFS using queue\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\ngraph-bfs:\n  0 → 1 → 3\n  ↓   ↓\n  2 → 4\n\n  Queue: [0]\n  visited: [T, F, F, F, F]\n\n  Pop 0 → queue [1, 2]\n  visited: [T, T, T, F, F]\n\n  Pop 1 → queue [2, 3]\n  visited: [T, T, T, T, F]\n\n  Pop 2 → queue [3]\n  visited: [T, T, T, T, F]\n\n  Pop 3 → queue [4]\n  visited: [T, T, T, T, T]\n\n  Pop 4 (already visited)\n  BFS Order: 0 → 1 → 2 → 3 → 4\n```\nBreadth-First Search (BFS) is a graph traversal algorithm that explores nodes level by level starting from a given source, guaranteeing that nodes closer to the source are visited before nodes farther away. The graph is represented using an adjacency list where each node stores a vector of its neighboring nodes. BFS employs a queue and a visited boolean array to track processed nodes. The algorithm begins by marking the source node (node 0) as visited and enqueuing it. In each iteration, a node u is dequeued and processed (typically printed), then every neighbor v of u is examined. If v has not been visited, it is marked visited and enqueued for later processing. This ensures each node enters the queue at most once and all nodes at distance k are processed before any node at distance k+1, making BFS a level-order traversal. For a dry run on a graph with 5 nodes and edges (0-1, 0-2, 1-3, 1-4, 2-4, 3-4): BFS from node 0 visits 0, then its immediate neighbors 1 and 2, then the next level nodes 3 and 4, producing order 0 1 2 3 4. Edge cases to consider include disconnected graphs where BFS from a single source will not traverse the entire graph and must be run from every unvisited node to produce a complete forest traversal. A completely isolated node with no edges will simply be visited and the queue will immediately become empty. Self-loops and parallel edges do not affect correctness as long as visited marking prevents re-enqueuing. The time complexity is O(V+E) because each vertex is enqueued once and each adjacency list edge is examined once. The space complexity is O(V) for the queue and visited array.",
