    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <stack>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n, m; cin >> n >> m;\n  vector<vector<int>> g(n);\n  for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {\n    int u, v; cin >> u >> v;\n    g[u].push_back(v); g[v].push_back(u);\n  }\n\n  // DFS using stack or recursion\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\ngraph-dfs:\n  0 → 1 → 3\n  ↓   ↓\n  2 → 4\n\n  Call Stack:\n  dfs(0) visit 0\n  └─ dfs(1) visit 1\n     ├─ dfs(3) visit 3\n     │  └─ dfs(4) visit 4\n     │     └─ backtrack\n     └─ dfs(2) visit 2\n        └─ backtrack\n\n  DFS Order: 0 → 1 → 3 → 4 → 2\n```\nDepth-First Search (DFS) is a graph traversal algorithm that explores a path to its deepest node before backtracking and exploring alternative branches. The graph is represented as an adjacency list. DFS can be implemented recursively using the call stack or iteratively using an explicit stack. The recursive approach defines a function dfs(u) that marks node u as visited, processes it, and then recursively calls dfs(v) for every unvisited neighbor v. The recursion naturally backtracks when all neighbors of a node have been exhausted. The iterative approach uses an explicit stack: push the source node, and while the stack is non-empty, pop the top node, and if unvisited, mark it, process it, and push all its unvisited neighbors. The order of visitation may differ between recursive and iterative implementations because the iterative version processes nodes in reverse order of neighbor list due to LIFO behavior. For a dry run on a graph with 5 nodes and edges (0-1, 0-2, 1-3, 1-4, 2-4, 3-4) using recursion: dfs(0) visits 0, calls dfs(1), which visits 1 and calls dfs(3), which visits 3 and calls dfs(4), which visits 4. After dfs(4) returns, dfs(3) returns, then dfs(1) calls dfs(2), which visits 2. The DFS order is 0 1 3 4 2 assuming neighbors in ascending order. Edge cases include disconnected graphs where DFS must be initiated from every unvisited node. For a tree, DFS produces the depth-first traversal. For a single node with no edges, DFS simply visits that node and stops. The time complexity is O(V+E) since each vertex and each edge is examined once. The space complexity is O(V) for the visited array plus the recursion stack depth, which can be up to V in the worst case of a skewed graph forming a single long chain.",
