    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <queue>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n, m; cin >> n >> m;\n  vector<vector<int>> g(n);\n  vector<int> indeg(n, 0);\n  for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) { int u, v; cin >> u >> v; g[v].push_back(u); indeg[u]++; }\n\n  queue<int> q;\n  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) if (indeg[i] == 0) q.push(i);\n  int cnt = 0;\n  while (!q.empty()) { int u = q.front(); q.pop(); cnt++; for (int v : g[u]) if (--indeg[v] == 0) q.push(v); }\n\n  cout << (cnt == n ? \"Yes\" : \"No\") << endl;\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\ncourse-schedule:\n  Prerequisites: [1,0] means 0→1\n  0 → 1 → 2 → 3\n  indeg: [0, 1, 1, 1]\n\n  Queue: [0]\n  Pop 0 → indeg[1]=0, queue [1]\n  Pop 1 → indeg[2]=0, queue [2]\n  Pop 2 → indeg[3]=0, queue [3]\n  Pop 3 → all done! cnt=4 == n → Yes\n\n  Cycle case:\n  0 ↔ 1\n  indeg: [1, 1]\n  Queue empty (no indegree-0) → cnt=0 < 2 → No\n```\nThe Course Schedule problem asks whether it is possible to finish all n courses given prerequisite pairs [u, v] meaning 'you must take course v before course u'. This is equivalent to detecting a cycle in a directed graph: if the prerequisite graph contains a cycle, it is impossible to complete all courses. The graph is built as an adjacency list where an edge v->u means v must come before u. We also compute the indegree (number of incoming edges) for each node. The algorithm uses Kahn's topological sort via BFS. First, all nodes with indegree 0 (courses with no prerequisites) are enqueued. While the queue is non-empty, we dequeue a course u, increment a processed counter, and for each neighbor v of u, decrement indegree[v]. If indegree[v] becomes 0, all of v's prerequisites have been satisfied, so we enqueue v. After processing, if the processed count equals n, all courses can be finished and a valid ordering exists. If the count is less than n, a cycle exists in the prerequisite graph and it is impossible to finish all courses. For a dry run with 4 courses and prerequisites (1->0, 2->1, 3->2): edge direction is 0->1, 1->2, 2->3 (v->u means v before u). Indegrees: [0,1,1,1]. Queue=[0]. Dequeue 0 -> indeg[1]=0, enqueue 1. Dequeue 1 -> indeg[2]=0, enqueue 2. Dequeue 2 -> indeg[3]=0, enqueue 3. Dequeue 3. Count=4=n, so Yes. For a cycle (1->0, 0->1): indeg=[1,1]. Queue empty initially (no indegree-0 node), count=0 < 2, so No. Edge cases include courses with no prerequisites forming isolated nodes with indegree 0, and self-loop prerequisites which create immediate cycles. Time complexity is O(V+E) and space is O(V).",
