    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <unordered_map>\nusing namespace std;\n\nclass Node { public: int val; vector<Node*> neighbors; Node(int v): val(v){} };\n\nNode* cloneGraph(Node* node) {\n  if (!node) return nullptr;\n  unordered_map<Node*, Node*> mp;\n  return mp[node];\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\nclone-graph:\n  Original:          Clone:\n  0 ---- 1            0' ---- 1'\n  |      |            |       |\n  2 ---- 3            2' ---- 3'\n\n  DFS clone(0):\n  mp[0]=new Node(0)\n  |- clone(1): mp[1]=new Node(1)\n  |  |- clone(0) -> in map, return mp[0]\n  |  |- clone(3): mp[3]=new Node(3)\n  |     |- clone(1) -> in map\n  |     |- clone(2): mp[2]=new Node(2)\n  |        |- clone(0) -> in map\n  |        |- clone(3) -> in map\n\n  Map ensures each node cloned exactly once\n```\nClone Graph requires creating a deep copy of a connected undirected graph where each node carries an integer value and a list of references to its neighbors. The challenge is preserving the graph structure without creating duplicate copies of the same node. The solution uses a hashmap (unordered_map) mapping each original node to its cloned counterpart. We perform a DFS traversal starting from the given node. When visiting a node for the first time, we create a new Node with the same value, store the mapping, and then recursively clone all its neighbors. If a node is already in the map, we return the already-created clone, ensuring structural sharing matches the original. The base case is a null input node returning null. For a dry run on a 4-node square graph 0-1-3-2-0: start dfs(0), create clone 0', map[0]=0'. For each neighbor (1,2), clone recursively: dfs(1) creates 1', maps it, clones neighbors (0 in map, 3 not yet) -> dfs(3) creates 3', maps it, clones neighbors (1 in map, 2 not yet) -> dfs(2) creates 2', maps it, neighbors (0,3) already in map. All nodes cloned, structure preserved. Edge cases include single node with no neighbors (return a new node with empty neighbors), null graph (return null), and cyclic graphs where the hashmap prevents infinite loops. Time complexity is O(V+E) since each edge is traversed once. Space complexity is O(V) for the hashmap and recursion stack.",
    complexity: {"time":"O(V+E)","space":"O(V)"},
    sheet: "Blind 75",
    solution_code: "unordered_map<Node*,Node*> mp; function<Node*(Node*)> dfs=[&](Node* u){if(!u)return u; if(mp.count(u))return mp[u]; Node* c=new Node(u->val); mp[u]=c; for(Node* v:u->neighbors)c->neighbors.push_back(dfs(v)); return c;}; return dfs(node);",
    techniques: ["tree-dfs", "tree-bfs"],
