    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <queue>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n, m; cin >> n >> m;\n  vector<vector<int>> g(n);\n  vector<int> indeg(n, 0);\n  for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) { int u, v; cin >> u >> v; g[v].push_back(u); indeg[u]++; }\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\ncourse-schedule-ii:\n  Prerequisites: [1,0]->0->1, [2,1]->1->2, [3,2]->2->3\n  Graph: 0 -> 1 -> 2 -> 3\n  indeg: [0, 1, 1, 1]\n\n  Queue: [0]\n  Pop 0 -> indeg[1]=0 -> queue [1], order [0]\n  Pop 1 -> indeg[2]=0 -> queue [2], order [0,1]\n  Pop 2 -> indeg[3]=0 -> queue [3], order [0,1,2]\n  Pop 3 -> order [0,1,2,3]\n\n  Return order if cnt == n, else empty\n```\nCourse Schedule II extends Course Schedule by requiring the actual topological ordering, not just a boolean. The problem is solved using Kahn's algorithm (BFS with indegree tracking). Build an adjacency list where edge v->u means v is a prerequisite of u. Compute indegree (incoming edge count) for each node. Initialize a queue with all nodes having indegree 0 (no prerequisites). While the queue is non-empty, dequeue a node, append it to the result order list, and for each neighbor, decrement its indegree. If any neighbor's indegree reaches 0, enqueue it. After processing, if the order list size equals n, return the order; otherwise return an empty list indicating a cycle. Edge cases include multiple valid orderings (any is acceptable), courses with no prerequisites (processed first), and cycles making completion impossible. Time complexity is O(V+E) and space is O(V).",
