    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n; cin >> n;\n  vector<vector<int>> adj(n, vector<int>(n));\n  for(int i=0;i<n;i++) for(int j=0;j<n;j++) cin >> adj[i][j];\n\n  vector<bool> vis(n, false);\n  int provinces = 0;\n  for(int i=0;i<n;i++) if(!vis[i]) { provinces++; }\n  cout << provinces << endl;\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\nnumber-of-provinces:\n  Matrix:           Graph:\n  1 1 0            0 - 1   2\n  1 1 0            (comp 1) (comp 2)\n  0 0 1\n\n  vis: [F, F, F]  provinces=0\n  i=0: vis[0]=F -> DFS(0) visits 0,1 -> vis[T,T,F] provinces=1\n  i=1: vis[1]=T -> skip\n  i=2: vis[2]=F -> DFS(2) visits 2 -> vis[T,T,T] provinces=2\n  Result: 2 provinces\n```\nThe Number of Provinces problem counts connected components in an undirected graph represented as an adjacency matrix where isConnected[i][j]=1 means there is a direct edge between cities i and j. The solution uses DFS traversal with a visited boolean array. For each unvisited city i, we increment the province count and perform DFS to mark all reachable cities from i as visited. DFS iterates over all cities j; if isConnected[i][j]==1 and j is unvisited, recursively call DFS on j. This approach correctly handles the symmetric matrix property. Edge cases include an empty or single-city matrix returning 0 or 1. A fully connected graph returns 1, while a graph with no edges returns n provinces. BFS or Union-Find are alternative solutions. Time complexity is O(n^2) due to matrix traversal, and space is O(n) for the visited array and recursion stack.",
