    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n, m; cin >> n >> m;\n  vector<int> trust_count(n+1,0), trusted_by(n+1,0);\n  for(int i=0;i<m;i++){int u,v;cin>>u>>v; trust_count[u]++; trusted_by[v]++;}\n  for(int i=1;i<=n;i++) if(trust_count[i]==0 && trusted_by[i]==n-1) { cout << i; return 0; }\n  cout << -1;\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\nfind-the-town-judge:\n  Trust pairs: (1->2), (3->2)\n\n  Trust count (outgoing):  [0, 1, 0, 1]\n  Trusted count (incoming): [0, 0, 2, 0]\n\n  Judge: trust_count[i]==0 && trusted_by[i]==n-1\n  Node 2: out[2]=0, in[2]=2 == 3-1=2 -> Judge is 2\n```\nIn a town of n people, the town judge is the person who trusts nobody and is trusted by everyone else. The problem reduces to counting indegree and outdegree for each node in a directed trust graph. We maintain two arrays: trust_count (outdegree: how many people this person trusts) and trusted_by (indegree: how many people trust this person). For each trust pair (a,b), increment trust_count[a] (a trusts someone) and trusted_by[b] (b is trusted by someone). After processing all pairs, scan from person 1 to n. The judge satisfies trust_count[i]==0 (judge trusts nobody) and trusted_by[i]==n-1 (everyone else trusts the judge). Edge cases include no judge existing (return -1), n=1 with no edges (person 1 is judge by definition since they trust nobody and are trusted by 0 others, which equals n-1=0), and multiple people satisfying both conditions (should not happen, but return -1). Time complexity is O(n+m) and space is O(n).",
    complexity: {"time":"O(n+m)","space":"O(n)"},
