    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <queue>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n, m, q; cin >> n >> m >> q;\n  vector<vector<int>> g(n);\n  vector<int> indeg(n, 0);\n  for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) { int u, v; cin >> u >> v; g[u].push_back(v); indeg[v]++; }\n\n  // Floyd-Warshall reachability matrix or BFS from each node\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\ncourse-schedule-iv:\n  n=5, prereqs: 0->1->2->3->4\n\n  Floyd-Warshall reachability:\n  init: reach[i][i]=1, edges set reach[u][v]=1\n\n  k=0: no change\n  k=1: reach[0][2]=1 (via 0->1->2)\n  k=2: reach[0][3]=1, reach[1][3]=1\n  k=3: reach[0][4]=1, reach[1][4]=1, reach[2][4]=1\n  k=4: no change\n\n  queries:\n  [1,4]: reach[1][4]=1 -> true\n  [4,1]: reach[4][1]=0 -> false\n\n  Output: true false\n```\nCompute transitive closure using Floyd-Warshall (O(n^3) with n<=100) or BFS from each node (O(n*(n+m))). Build adjacency graph of prerequisites. For each query [a,b], check if a can reach b. Floyd-Warshall uses a boolean reachability matrix and 3 nested loops over k,i,j. Edge cases: self-prerequisites (always true), disconnected courses. Time O(n^3), Space O(n^2).",
    complexity: {"time":"O(n^3)","space":"O(n^2)"},
    sheet: "LeetCode",
    solution_code: "vector<vector<bool>> reach(n, vector<bool>(n)); for(int i=0;i<n;i++)reach[i][i]=1; for(auto& p:prereqs)reach[p[0]][p[1]]=1; for(int k=0;k<n;k++)for(int i=0;i<n;i++)for(int j=0;j<n;j++)if(reach[i][k]&&reach[k][j])reach[i][j]=1;",
