    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <queue>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n, m; cin >> n >> m;\n  vector<vector<int>> g(n);\n  vector<int> indeg(n, 0);\n  for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {\n    int u, v; cin >> u >> v;\n    g[u].push_back(v); indeg[v]++;\n  }\n  int q; cin >> q;\n\n  // Kahn's + Floyd reachability matrix\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\ncourse-schedule-iv:\n  0 → 1 → 2 → 3\n\n  Reachability matrix (Floyd):\n    \\ 0 1 2 3\n  0│ T T T T\n  1│ F T T T\n  2│ F F T T\n  3│ F F F T\n\n  Query: 0→3 ? Reachable[0][3] = T → true\n  Query: 3→0 ? Reachable[3][0] = F → false\n\n  BFS from each node:\n  From 0: reachable {0,1,2,3}\n  From 1: reachable {1,2,3}\n  From 2: reachable {2,3}\n  From 3: reachable {3}\n```\nRun BFS/DFS from each course to compute transitive closure or use Floyd-Warshall (n<=100). For each query (u,v), check if v is reachable from u. Kahn's algorithm with indegree tracking can also produce topological order, then propagate reachability forward. Time O(n^3) with Floyd or O(n*(n+m)) with per-node BFS.",
    complexity: {"time":"O(n*(n+m))","space":"O(n^2)"},
    sheet: "Striver A2Z",
    solution_code: "vector<bitset<100>> rch(n); vector<int> indeg(n); vector<vector<int>> g(n), rg(n); queue<int> q; for(int i=0;i<n;i++){rch[i][i]=1;if(!indeg[i])q.push(i);} while(!q.empty()){int u=q.front();q.pop();for(int v:g[u]){rch[v]|=rch[u];if(--indeg[v]==0)q.push(v);}} for(int i=0;i<q;i++){int a,b;cin>>a>>b;cout<<(rch[b][a]?\"true\":\"false\")<<\" \";}",
