    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <unordered_map>\n#include <queue>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  // Build graph: recipe depends on ingredients\n  // Kahn's algorithm: initially enqueue supplies\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\nfind-all-possible-recipes:\n  Recipes: bread=[flour,yeast], sandwich=[bread,ham]\n  Supplies: flour, yeast, ham, bread\n\n  Graph:\n  flour → bread\n  yeast → bread\n  bread → sandwich\n  ham → sandwich\n\n  Indeg: bread=2, sandwich=2\n  Queue (supplies): flour, yeast, ham, bread (if supplied)\n\n  Pop flour → bread indeg-- (now 1)\n  Pop yeast → bread indeg-- (now 0) → enqueue bread\n  Pop bread → sandwich indeg-- (now 1)\n  Pop ham → sandwich indeg-- (now 0) → enqueue sandwich\n\n  Output: bread, sandwich\n```\nModel recipes as graph nodes. Each recipe has incoming edges from its ingredients. Supplies are nodes with indegree 0. Use Kahn's algorithm: enqueue all supplies, process queue, when recipe's indegree reaches 0 it becomes available. Time O(n+m), Space O(n+m).",
    complexity: {"time":"O(n+m)","space":"O(n+m)"},
    sheet: "Striver A2Z",
    solution_code: "unordered_map<string,int> idx; for(int i=0;i<recipes.size();i++)idx[recipes[i]]=i; vector<int> indeg(recipes.size()); vector<vector<int>> g(recipes.size()); for(int i=0;i<recipes.size();i++)for(auto& ing:ingredients[i])if(idx.count(ing)){g[i].push_back(idx[ing]);indeg[idx[ing]]++;} queue<int> q; for(auto& s:supplies)if(idx.count(s)&&!indeg[idx[s]])q.push(idx[s]); vector<string> res; while(!q.empty()){int u=q.front();q.pop();res.push_back(recipes[u]);for(int v:g[u])if(--indeg[v]==0)q.push(v);} for(auto& r:res)cout<<r<<\" \";",
