    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n; cin >> n;\n  vector<int> nums(n);\n  for(int i=0;i<n;i++)cin>>nums[i];\n\n  // ans[i] = nums[nums[i]]\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\nbuild-array-from-permutation:\n  nums = [2, 0, 1, 3, 4, 5]\n\n  ans[0] = nums[nums[0]] = nums[2] = 1\n  ans[1] = nums[nums[1]] = nums[0] = 2\n  ans[2] = nums[nums[2]] = nums[1] = 0\n  ans[3] = nums[nums[3]] = nums[3] = 3\n  ans[4] = nums[nums[4]] = nums[4] = 4\n  ans[5] = nums[nums[5]] = nums[5] = 5\n\n  Result: [2, 0, 1, 3, 4, 5]  ...wait, that's same as input\n  Let me recalculate: ans = [nums[2], nums[0], nums[1], nums[3], nums[4], nums[5]]\n  = [1, 2, 0, 3, 4, 5]\n```\nFrom given nums array where nums is a permutation, compute ans[i] = nums[nums[i]] for each i. This is a direct mapping problem. The challenge is doing it in O(1) extra space by encoding both values in the same array using modulo arithmetic. Time O(n), Space O(1).",
