    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <unordered_map>\n#include <vector>\n#include <queue>\n#include <string>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n; cin >> n;\n  unordered_map<string, vector<string>> g;\n  unordered_map<string, int> indeg;\n  // Build graph, then Hierholzer or Kahn's\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\nitinerary-reconstruction:\n  Tickets: JFK→SFO, JFK→ATL, SFO→ATL, ATL→JFK, ATL→SFO\n  Start: JFK\n\n  Graph:\n  JFK → SFO (lexicographically larger)\n  JFK → ATL (lexicographically smaller = prefer)\n  SFO → ATL\n  ATL → JFK\n  ATL → SFO\n\n  Hierholzer's (post-order DFS):\n  Start JFK → ATL → JFK → SFO → ATL → SFO\n  Reverse path: JFK→ATL→JFK→SFO→ATL→SFO\n\n  Using multiset for lexicographic order:\n  dfs(JFK): visit ATL(min), dfs(ATL): visit JFK, dfs(JFK): visit SFO, dfs(SFO): visit ATL, dfs(ATL): visit SFO, done\n  ⇒ reverse: JFK ATL JFK SFO ATL SFO\n```\nUse Hierholzer's algorithm (DFS post-order) with a multiset for lexicographic order. Since Eulerian path exists (exactly one node has outdeg-indeg=1 = start, all others balanced). Traverse edges in lexical order, backtrack/record when stuck. Reverse of recorded order is the path. Time O(E log E), Space O(V+E).",
