    test_cases: [{"input":"3 2\n0 1\n0 2","expected":"0 1 2\\n0 2 1"}],
    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <queue>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n, m; cin >> n >> m;\n  vector<vector<int>> g(n);\n  vector<int> indeg(n);\n  for(int i=0;i<m;i++){int u,v;cin>>u>>v;g[u].push_back(v);indeg[v]++;}\n\n  // Backtracking with indegree 0 candidates\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\nall-task-orderings:\n  0 → 1\n  ↓\n  2\n\n  All topological orders:\n  Path 1: 0→1→2 (0 before 1, 0 before 2)\n  Path 2: 0→2→1 (0 before 1, 0 before 2)\n\n  Backtracking:\n  candidates = [0], pick 0\n    candidates = [1,2], pick 1\n      candidates = [2], pick 2 → [0,1,2]\n    bounce, pick 2\n      candidates = [1], pick 1 → [0,2,1]\n\n  n <= 15 ensures manageable state space.\n```\nBacktracking with indegree tracking. At each step, iterate over all nodes with indegree 0, pick one, decrement neighbors, recurse, restore. Use queue or set for O(1) candidate access. Time O(n! * n) worst-case but n<=15 keeps it feasible for sparse DAGs. Space O(n) for recursion.",
