    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n#include <queue>\n#include <tuple>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n, m, k; cin >> n >> m >> k;\n  vector<vector<int>> grid(n, vector<int>(m));\n  for(int i=0;i<n;i++)for(int j=0;j<m;j++)cin>>grid[i][j];\n\n  // BFS with state (r,c,eliminationsLeft)\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\ngrid-elimination:\n  Grid: 0 0 0         k=1\n        0 1 0\n        0 0 0\n\n  BFS state: (r,c,kLeft)\n  visited[r][c][k] tracks min steps to reach (r,c) with k eliminations left\n\n  Path without elimination: 0,0→0,1→0,2→1,2→2,2 = 4 steps\n  Path through obstacle (1,1): 0,0→0,1→1,1(eliminate)→2,1→2,2 = 4 steps\n\n  Both cost 4. Answer: 4\n```\nBFS over state space (r, c, k). visited[r][c][k] = min steps. From each cell, try 4 directions. If cell is 0, newK=k. If cell is 1 and k>0, use elimination. Stop when reaching (n-1,m-1). Time O(n*m*k), Space O(n*m*k).",
