    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n, m; cin >> n >> m;\n  vector<vector<int>> grid(n, vector<int>(m));\n  for(int i=0;i<n;i++)for(int j=0;j<m;j++)cin>>grid[i][j];\n\n  // DFS backtracking (n,m <= 15)\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\nmax-gold-path:\n  Grid: 0  6  0\n        5  8  7\n        0  9  0\n\n  Start at each non-zero cell, DFS with backtracking:\n  (0,1)=6 → (1,1)=8 → (1,2)=7 (sum=21)\n                      → (2,1)=9 → (1,0)=5 (sum=28) wait 6+8+9+7+5=35? No, can't go 9→5 and 7 at same time\n                      Actually path: 6→8→9→7 = 30? 6+8+9+7=30 but that revisits?\n\n  Let's trace: 6→8→9(sum=23), from 9: 7→6(visited) or 8(visited), or 5: 5→8(visited) or 0\n  So max = 6+8+7=21 or 6+8+9=23 or 5+8+7=20 or 5+8+9=22 or 9+8+7=24\n  Answer: 24 (path: 9→8→7)\n```\nDFS backtracking from each cell with gold. Track visited cells to avoid revisiting. Max gold = max path sum. n,m <= 15 keeps state manageable. Time O(4^(n*m)), Space O(n*m) with pruning for zeros.",
