    solution_template: "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint main() {\n  int n, m; cin >> n >> m;\n  // DSU with size 2n: i and i+n represent opposite sets\n\n  return 0;\n}",
    approach: "\n\nDiagram:\n```\npossible-bipartition:\n  n=4, dislikes: [1,2], [1,3], [2,4]\n\n  DSU size 2n:\n  For each edge (u,v):\n    union(u, v+n) → u in same set as v's complement\n    union(v, u+n) → v in same set as u's complement\n\n  Edge (1,2): union(1,6), union(2,5)\n  Edge (1,3): union(1,7), union(3,5)\n  Edge (2,4): union(2,8), union(4,6)\n\n  If at any point find(u)==find(v), conflict! Not bipartite.\n  No conflict → Bipartite ✓\n\n  With triangle: 1-2, 2-3, 3-1\n  Edge (3,1): find(3)==find(1)? find(3)=7? find(1)=6? 7!=6 → ok\n  But union(3,5) and union(1,7)... eventually conflict arises.\n```\nExtended DSU: nodes 1..n are set A, n+1..2n are set B. For each dislike (u,v), union(u, v+n) and union(v, u+n). If find(u)==find(v), not bipartite. Time O((n+m)*alpha(n)), Space O(n).",
